@@cards @@column
@@row
  \card{Noisy Channel Model}{Shannon's metaphor of the noisy channel and decoding for the transmission of language through media like communication channels and speech acoustics.

  Shannon's use of entropy from thermodynamics measures the information capacity of a channel, or the information content of a language; performed the first measure of the entropy of English using probabilistic techniques.

  Sound spectrograph was developed (Koenig et al., 1946), and instrumental phonetics that laid the groundwork for later work in speech recognition. First machine speech recognizers were developed back in the early 1950s.}
@@

@@row
  \card{Foundational Insights: 1940s - 1950s}{### **Formal language theory**
  Chomsky (1956), drawing the idea of a finite state Markov process from Shannon's work, first considered finite-state machines as a way to characterize a grammar, and defined a finite-state language as a language generated by a finite-state grammar.

  These early models led to the field of formal language theory, which used algebra and set theory to define formal languages as senquence of symbols. This includes the context-free grammar that we will later go into detail in an individual article, first defined by Chomsky (1956) for natural languages. }

  \card{Automata Theory and The Ground Work}{Turing the founding father of computer science's work led first to the creation of a kind of computing element closer to propositional logic. And then Kleene (1951) and (1956) developed finite state automata and regular expressions.

  Shannon (1948) then applied probabilistic models of discrete Markov processes to automata for language (continued).}
@@


@@row

  \card{The Merging of Two Cultures}{### Speech and Language Processing: Symbolic
  _Language Theory_: The work of Chomsky and others on formal language theory and generative syntax throughout the late 1950s and early to mid 1960s, and work of many linguists and computational scientists on parsing algorithms, initially top-down and bottom-up and via dynamic programming.

  One of the earliest complete parsing systems was Zelig Harris’s Transformations and Discourse Analysis Project (TDAP), which was implemented between 1958-1959 at the University of Pennsylvania(Harris, 1962).

  _Artificial Intelligence_: In the summer of 1956 John McCarthy, Marvin Minsky, Cloude Shannon, and Nathaniel Rochester brought together a group of researchers for a two-month workshop on what they decided to call artificial intelligence (AI).

  The major focus of the new field was the work on reasoning and logic typified by Newell and Simon’s work on the Logic Theorist and the General Problem Solver.

  _At this point early natural language understanding systems were built._

  These were simple systems that worked in single domains mainly by a combinations of pattern matching and keybord search with simple heuristics for reasoning and question-answering. By the late 60s more formal logical systems were developed.

  }

  \card{Paradigms Develop}{Baysian method was beginning to be applied to the problem of optical character recognition.

Bledsoe and Browning (1959) built a Bayesian system for text-recognition that used a large dictionary and comptuted the likelihood of each observed letter sequecne given each word in the dictionary by multiplying the likelihoods for each letter.

Mosteller and Wallace (1964) applied Bayesian methods to the problem of authorship attribution on the Federalist papers.

The first on-line corpora: the Brown corpus of American English, a 1 million word collecton of samples from 500 written texts from different genres (newspapers, novels, non-fiction, academic, etc.), which was assembled at Brown University in 1963-64.

Development of speech recognition algorithms, particularly the user of Hidden Markov Model and the metaphors of the noisy channel and decoding, developed inependently by personnel at IBM, and by Baker at Carnegie Mellon University.
}
@@

@@row
  \card{Empiricism Returns}{### **Finite-state Models Redux: 1983-1993**
  Finite-state models began to receive attention again after work on finite-state phonology and morphology by Kaplan and Kay (1981) and finite-state models of syntax by Church (1980).

  Return of empiricism; most notably the rise of probabilistic models throughout speech and langauge processing, influenced thoroughly by the work at IBM Thomas J. Watson Research Center on probablistic models of speech recognition.

  These probabilisitic methods are other such data-driven approaches spread into part-of-speech tagging, parsing and attachment ambiguities, and [connectionist](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connectionism) approaches from speech recognition to semantics. These are the early predecessor approaches of the large neural language models we see today.}
@@
